The aim of the European Union's action is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exercise more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre which the system recognizes on the brake pedal using the brake strength carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exercise this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for Bosch vehicles, one third of the drivers involved in an accident, before the collision, did not come to the brake pedal at all, and half of them had not been fully braked.
