The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus the braking distance that a car places at the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrian damage could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even less accidents - it is expected that every fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency brake systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or camera) and warns the driver while already exercising light pressure on the brakes.
